e du Latin Non Classique: Essai d'une Methode de Synthese|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1515/prbs.1992.4.2.91|journal=Probus|volume=4|issue=2|pages=|doi=10.1515/prbs.1992.4.2.91|issn=0921-4771|via=}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Hall, Robert Anderson, 1911-|url=http://worldcat.org/oclc/422266905|title=Proto-Romance phonology|date=1976|publisher=Elsevier|isbn=0-444-00183-2|oclc=422266905}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Hall, Robert A. (Robert Anderson), 1911-1997.|first=|url=http://worldcat.org/oclc/10773070|title=Proto-Romance Morphology|date=1983|publisher=John Benjamins Pub. Co|year=|isbn=90-272-3522-8|location=|pages=|oclc=10773070}}\n* {{Cite journal|last=De Dardel|first=Robert|last2=W\u00fcest|first2=Jakob|date=1993|title=Les syst\u00e8mes casuels du prototoman|url=https://elibrary.narr.digital/article/99.125005/vox199310025|journal=Vox Romanica|volume=52|issue=1|pages=25-65|issn=0042-899X|via=eLibrary}}\n*Alkire, Ti; Rosen, Rosen (July 2010). ''Romance Languages: A Historical Introduction''. New York: Cambridge University Press. ISBN <bdi>9780521717847</bdi>.\n*{{Cite book|last=Vincent|first=Nigel|title=Early and Late Latin: Continuity or Change?|last2=Adams|first2=J. N.|last3=Maltby|first3=Robert|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=2016|isbn=978-1-107-13225-2|location=|pages=}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Wright|first=Roger|title=Late Latin and Early Romance in Spain and Carolingian France|publisher=Francis Cairns|year=1982|isbn=0-905205-12-X|location=Liverpool|pages=}}\n[[Category:Latin]]\n", "name_user": "Excelsius", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Proto-Romance_Language"}
{"title_page": "Leonard Schrader", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name = Leonard Schrader\n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1943|11|30}}\n| birth_place = [[Grand Rapids, Michigan]]\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|2006|11|2|1943|11|30}}\n| death_place = [[Los Angeles, California]]\n| spouse = Chieko Schrader (1977&ndash;2006)\n| years_active = 1974&ndash;2006\n}}\n\n'''Leonard Schrader''' (November 30, 1943 &ndash; November 2, 2006) was an [[United States|American]] [[screenwriter]] and [[Film director|director]], most notable for his ability to write [[Japanese language]] films and for his many collaborations with his brother, [[Paul Schrader]]. He earned an [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]] nomination for the screenplay he wrote for the film ''[[Kiss of the Spider Woman (film)|Kiss of the Spider Woman]]''.\n\n==Early life and college==\nBorn in [[Grand Rapids, Michigan]], Schrader was brought up in a strict [[Calvinism|Dutch Calvinist]] family and did not see his first film until he was an adult. In 1968, he finished his [[Master of Fine Arts|MFA]] at the [[University of Iowa]]'s Writer's Workshop where he studied with [[Nelson Algren]], [[Kurt Vonnegut]], [[Richard Yates (novelist)|Richard Yates]], [[Robert Coover]], [[Jos\u00e9 Donoso]] and [[Jorge Luis Borges]].\n\n==Japan==\nAfter graduating, Schrader left Grand Rapids in [[the Midwest]] and escaped the draft by moving to Japan to teach. (According to [[Peter Biskind]], in his book ''[[Easy Riders, Raging Bulls]]'', Schrader left the U.S. when he received a draft induction notice and didn't return until he was 28 years old - and thus ineligible for the draft.)\n\nBetween 1969-73 Schrader escaped even further, slipping by night into the subculture of the [[Yamaguchi-gumi]] (the dominant [[Yakuza]] gangster organization in the [[Kansai]] area of Japan, which includes [[Kobe]], [[Kyoto]] and [[Osaka]]), while by day teaching American Literature at [[Doshisha University]] and [[Kyoto University]].\n\nDuring his time in Japan he met his future wife, Chieko Schrader. They married in 1977.\n\nHis living family includes brother Paul Schrader, niece Molly, and nephew Sam.\n\n==Film career==\nHis experiences with the Yakuza in Japan led to a collaboration on a story with his brother, [[Paul Schrader]]. This resulted in the film ''[[The Yakuza]]'' (1974), starring [[Robert Mitchum]] and directed by [[Sydney Pollack]]. Leonard and Paul also co-wrote ''[[Blue Collar (film)|Blue Collar]]'' (1978), a story of defiant auto-workers in Detroit, directed by Paul Schrader starring [[Richard Pryor]] and [[Harvey Keitel]], and ''[[Old Boyfriends]]'' (1979), about a woman's cross-country trek to visit old flames, directed by [[Joan Tewkesbury]] and starring [[John Belushi]], [[Talia Shire]], [[Keith Carradine]], [[John Houseman]].\n\nSchrader's other screenplay credits include such popular Japanese-language films as Tora-san's ''Dream of Spring'' (1979), ''[[The Man Who Stole the Sun]]'' (Japan's Best Film of the Year in 1980), and ''Shonben Rider'' (1983). In 1982, with wife Chieko Schrader, he co-wrote ''[[The Killing of America]]'', a documentary tracing the origins of U.S. violence. During this production, Leonard Schrader collaborated with New York experimental filmmaker, [[David Weisman]].\n\nSchrader's background in [[Latin American literature]] and Weisman's experience with Brazil led them to develop ''[[Kiss of the Spider Woman (film)|Kiss of the Spider Woman]]'' together. Schrader's screenplay adaptation, based on the avant-garde novel by [[Argentina|Argentinian]] [[Manuel Puig]], earned him an [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]] nomination in 1986. (It also earned [[William Hurt]] an Academy Award for Best Actor.)\n\nSchrader met renowned Japanese novelist [[Yukio Mishima]] while living in Japan. For a decade after the author's ritual suicide in 1970, Schrader pursued the rights to Mishima's life, and working with his wife Chieko and brother Paul, he co-wrote the Japanese-language bio-pic ''[[Mishima: A Life in Four Chapters]]'' executive-produced in 1984 by [[George Lucas]] and [[Francis Ford Coppola]], and directed by [[Paul Schrader]].\n\nSchrader made his directorial debut with ''[[Naked Tango]]'' (1991) for which he also wrote the screenplay. Produced in Argentina, with the 1925 period 'look' overseen by Oscar-winning designer [[Milena Canonero]], the independent film starred [[Vincent D'Onofrio]], [[Mathilda May]], [[Esai Morales]], and the late [[Fernando Rey]].\n\n==Death==\nSchrader died in 2006 in [[Los Angeles, California]], twenty-eight days away from his 63rd birthday.\n\n==Selected filmography==\n*''[[The Yakuza]]'' (1974) (writer)\n*''[[Blue Collar (film)|Blue Collar]]'' (1978) (co-writer)\n*''[[Tora-san's Dream of Spring]]'' (1979) (co-writer)\n*''[[Taiy\u014d o Nusunda Otoko]]'' (English title: ''The Man Who Stole the Sun'') (1979) (writer) (Japan's Best Film of the Year, 1980)\n*''[[The Killing of America]]'' (1982) (writer, producer, director)\n*''[[Mishima: A Life in Four Chapters]]'' (1985) (writer, associate producer)\n*''[[Kiss of the Spider Woman (film)|Kiss of the Spider Woman]]'' (1985) (writer) ([[Academy Awards|Academy Award]]-nominee)\n*''[[Naked Tango]]'' (1990) (writer, director)\n\n==Teaching==\n*From 1996 to 1999, Schrader taught the screenwriting Master's Thesis class at the [[University of Southern California]].\n*From 1999 to 2003, Schrader taught at [[Chapman University]] where he was an associate professor of film.\n*From 2003 until his death, Schrader was Senior Filmmaker-in-Residence at the [[American Film Institute]] where he chaired the Screenwriting Department and taught graduate screenwriting.\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|id=0775055|name=Leonard Schrader}}\n*[http://www.leonardschradercollection.com/ Leonard's legendary collection of rare Lobby Cards]\n*[https://www.nytimes.com/2006/11/07/obituaries/07schrader.html Obituary in ''The New York Times'']\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Schrader, Leonard}}\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:2006 deaths]]\n[[Category:American male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Writers from Grand Rapids, Michigan]]\n[[Category:American people of Dutch descent]]\n[[Category:American Calvinist and Reformed Christians]]\n[[Category:Iowa Writers' Workshop alumni]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in Japan]]\n[[Category:Chapman University faculty]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Michigan]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from California]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from Michigan]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name = Leonard Schrader\n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1943|11|30}}\n| birth_place = [[Grand Rapids, Michigan]]\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|2006|11|2|1943|11|30}}\n| death_place = [[Los Angeles, California]]\n| spouse = Chieko Schrader (1977&ndash;2006)\n| years_active = 1974&ndash;2006\n}}\n\n'''Leonard Schrader''' (November 30, 1943 &ndash; November 2, 2006) was an [[United States|American]] [[screenwriter]] and [[Film director|director]], most notable for his ability to write [[Japanese language]] films and for his many collaborations with his brother, [[Paul Schrader]]. He earned an [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]] nomination for the screenplay he wrote for the film ''[[Kiss of the Spider Woman (film)|Kiss of the Spider Woman]]''.\n\n==Early life and college==\nBorn in [[Grand Rapids, Michigan]], Schrader was brought up in a strict [[Calvinism|Dutch Calvinist]] family and did not see his first film until he was an adult. In 1968, he finished his [[Master of Fine Arts|MFA]] at the [[University of Iowa]]'s Writer's Workshop where he studied with [[Nelson Algren]], [[Kurt Vonnegut]], [[Richard Yates (novelist)|Richard Yates]], [[Robert Coover]], [[Jos\u00e9 Donoso]] and [[Jorge Luis Borges]].\n\n==Japan==\nAfter graduating, Schrader left Grand Rapids in [[the Midwest]] and escaped the draft by moving to Japan to teach. (According to [[Peter Biskind]], in his book ''[[Easy Riders, Raging Bulls]]'', Schrader left the U.S. when he received a draft induction notice and didn't return until he was 28 years old - and thus ineligible for the draft.)\n\nBetween 1969-73 Schrader escaped even further, slipping by night into the subculture of the [[Yamaguchi-gumi]] (the dominant [[Yakuza]] gangster organization in the [[Kansai]] area of Japan, which includes [[Kobe]], [[Kyoto]] and [[Osaka]]), while by day teaching American Literature at [[Doshisha University]] and [[Kyoto University]].\n\nDuring his time in Japan he met his future wife, Chieko Schrader. They married in 1977.\n\nHis living family includes brother Paul Schrader, niece Molly, and nephew Sam.\n\n==Film career==\nHis experiences with the Yakuza in Japan led to a collaboration on a story with his brother, [[Paul Schrader]]. This resulted in the film ''[[The Yakuza]]'' (1974), starring [[Robert Mitchum]] and directed by [[Sydney Pollack]]. Leonard and Paul also co-wrote ''[[Blue Collar (film)|Blue Collar]]'' (1978), a story of defiant auto-workers in Detroit, directed by Paul Schrader starring [[Richard Pryor]] and [[Harvey Keitel]], and ''[[Old Boyfriends]]'' (1979), about a woman's cross-country trek to visit old flames, directed by [[Joan Tewkesbury]] and starring [[John Belushi]], [[Talia Shire]], [[Keith Carradine]], [[John Houseman]].\n\nSchrader's other screenplay credits include such popular Japanese-language films as Tora-san's ''Dream of Spring'' (1979), ''[[The Man Who Stole the Sun]]'' (Japan's Best Film of the Year in 1980), and ''Shonben Rider'' (1983). In 1982, with wife Chieko Schrader, he co-wrote ''[[The Killing of America]]'', a documentary tracing the origins of U.S. violence. During this production, Leonard Schrader collaborated with New York experimental filmmaker, [[David Weisman]].\n\nSchrader's background in [[Latin American literature]] and Weisman's experience with Brazil led them to develop ''[[Kiss of the Spider Woman (film)|Kiss of the Spider Woman]]'' together. Schrader's screenplay adaptation, based on the avant-garde novel by [[Argentina|Argentinian]] [[Manuel Puig]], earned him an [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]] nomination in 1986. (It also earned [[William Hurt]] an Academy Award for Best Actor.)\n\nSchrader met renowned Japanese novelist [[Yukio Mishima]] while living in Japan. For a decade after the author's ritual suicide in 1970, Schrader pursued the rights to Mishima's life, and working with his wife Chieko and brother Paul, he co-wrote the Japanese-language bio-pic ''[[Mishima: A Life in Four Chapters]]'' executive-produced in 1984 by [[George Lucas]] and [[Francis Ford Coppola]], and directed by [[Paul Schrader]].\n\nSchrader made his directorial debut with ''[[Naked Tango]]'' (1991) for which he also wrote the screenplay. Produced in Argentina, with the 1925 period 'look' overseen by Oscar-winning designer [[Milena Canonero]], the independent film starred [[Vincent D'Onofrio]], [[Mathilda May]], [[Esai Morales]], and the late [[Fernando Rey]].\n\n==Death==\nSchrader died in 2006 in [[Los Angeles, California]].\n\n==Selected filmography==\n*''[[The Yakuza]]'' (1974) (writer)\n*''[[Blue Collar (film)|Blue Collar]]'' (1978) (co-writer)\n*''[[Tora-san's Dream of Spring]]'' (1979) (co-writer)\n*''[[Taiy\u014d o Nusunda Otoko]]'' (English title: ''The Man Who Stole the Sun'') (1979) (writer) (Japan's Best Film of the Year, 1980)\n*''[[The Killing of America]]'' (1982) (writer, producer, director)\n*''[[Mishima: A Life in Four Chapters]]'' (1985) (writer, associate producer)\n*''[[Kiss of the Spider Woman (film)|Kiss of the Spider Woman]]'' (1985) (writer) ([[Academy Awards|Academy Award]]-nominee)\n*''[[Naked Tango]]'' (1990) (writer, director)\n\n==Teaching==\n*From 1996 to 1999, Schrader taught the screenwriting Master's Thesis class at the [[University of Southern California]].\n*From 1999 to 2003, Schrader taught at [[Chapman University]] where he was an associate professor of film.\n*From 2003 until his death, Schrader was Senior Filmmaker-in-Residence at the [[American Film Institute]] where he chaired the Screenwriting Department and taught graduate screenwriting.\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|id=0775055|name=Leonard Schrader}}\n*[http://www.leonardschradercollection.com/ Leonard's legendary collection of rare Lobby Cards]\n*[https://www.nytimes.com/2006/11/07/obituaries/07schrader.html Obituary in ''The New York Times'']\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Schrader, Leonard}}\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:2006 deaths]]\n[[Category:American male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Writers from Grand Rapids, Michigan]]\n[[Category:American people of Dutch descent]]\n[[Category:American Calvinist and Reformed Christians]]\n[[Category:Iowa Writers' Workshop alumni]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in Japan]]\n[[Category:Chapman University faculty]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Michigan]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from California]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from Michigan]]\n", "name_user": "172.78.8.200", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eDeath)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leonard_Schrader"}
{"title_page": "TOI 1338", "text_new": "{{short description|Binary star system}}\n{{use dmy dates |date=January 2020}}\n{{starbox begin\n|name = TOI 1338\n}}\n{{starbox image\n|image = [[File:TOI1338-starmap.png|320px]]\n|caption = Position of TOI 1338 in Pictor\n|credit = \n}}\n{{Starbox observe\n| epoch = J2000\n| constell = [[Pictor]]\n| ra =  {{RA|06|08|31.94}}.<ref name=\"ExoFOP TESS\"/>\n| dec = {{DEC|-59|32|27.55}}.<ref name=\"ExoFOP TESS\"/>\n| appmag_v = 11.975\u00b10.025\n}}\n{{Starbox character\n| type = \n| class = \n| appmag_1_passband = \n| appmag_1 = \n| appmag_2_passband = \n| appmag_2 = \n| appmag_3_passband =\n| appmag_3 =\n| appmag_4_passband = \n| appmag_4 = \n| appmag_5_passband = \n| appmag_5 = \n| appmag_6_passband = \n| appmag_6 = \n| appmag_7_passband = \n| appmag_7 = \n| appmag_8_passband = \n| appmag_8 = \n| r-i = \n| v-r = \n| b-v = \n| u-b = \n| j-h = \n| j-k = \n| variable = \n}}\n{{Starbox astrometry\n| radial_v = 24.68\u00b18.08<ref name=\"Gaia\"/>\n| prop_mo_ra = -12.258\u00b10.037<ref name=\"Gaia\"/>\n| prop_mo_dec = 34.405\u00b10.041<ref name=\"Gaia\"/>\n| parallax = 2.4774\n| p_error = 0.0196\n| parallax_footnote = <ref name=\"Gaia\"/>\n| absmag_v =\n}}\n{{Starbox detail\n| source =\n| component1 = TOI 1338 A \n| mass=1.20<ref name=\"Martin et al\"/>\n| radius = \n| luminosity = \n| luminosity_bolometric =\n| luminosity_visual =\n| gravity = \n| temperature = \n| metal_fe = \n| rotation =\n| rotational_velocity =\n| age =\n| age_myr = \n| age_gyr = \n| component2 = TOI 1338 B\n| mass2 = 0.3250<ref name=\"Martin et al\"/>\n}}\n{{Starbox catalog\n| names = TYC 8533-950-1, EBLM J0608-59, 2MASS J06083197-5932280, RAVE J060832.0-593228\n}}\n{{Starbox reference\n| Simbad = TYC+8533-950-1\n| EPE = TOI-1338\n}}\n{{starbox end}}\n'''TOI 1338''' is a binary star system, discovered by [[TESS]], and TESS's first [[binary system]] confirmed to contain a planet, called a [[circumbinary planet]]. The system is 1,300 light-years away in the constellation [[Pictor]].<ref name=\"ExoFOP TESS\">{{Cite web|url=https://exofop.ipac.caltech.edu/tess/target.php?id=260128333|title=ExoFOP TIC 260128333|website=exofop.ipac.caltech.edu|access-date=2020-01-09}}</ref><ref name=\"Gaia\">{{Cite journal|last=Gaia Collaboration|date=2018-08-01|title=Gaia Data Release 2 - Summary of the contents and survey properties|url=https://www.aanda.org/articles/aa/abs/2018/08/aa33051-18/aa33051-18.html|journal=Astronomy & Astrophysics|language=en|volume=616|pages=A1|doi=10.1051/0004-6361/201833051|issn=0004-6361|doi-access=free}}</ref> The two stars with masses of about 1.2 and 0.325 {{solar mass|link=true}} revolve around each other every 14.6 days.<ref name=\"Martin et al\">{{Cite journal|last=Martin|first=David V.|last2=Triaud|first2=Amaury H. M. J.|last3=Udry|first3=Stephane|last4=Marmier|first4=Maxime|last5=Maxted|first5=Pierre F. L.|last6=Cameron|first6=Andrew Collier|last7=Hellier|first7=Coel|last8=Pepe|first8=Francesco|last9=Pollacco|first9=Don|last10=Segransan|first10=Damien|last11=West|first11=Richard|date=April 2019|title=The BEBOP radial-velocity survey for circumbinary planets I. Eight years of CORALIE observations of 47 single-line eclipsing binaries and abundance constraints on the masses of circumbinary planets|url=http://arxiv.org/abs/1901.01627|journal=Astronomy & Astrophysics|volume=624|pages=A68|doi=10.1051/0004-6361/201833669|issn=0004-6361|via=|doi-access=free}}</ref> \n==Nomenclature and history==\nThe acronym '''<big>\"TOI\"</big>''' refers to stars and exoplanets studied by TESS, and is short for: \"'''<big>T</big>'''ransiting Exoplanet Survey Satellite '''<big>O</big>'''bject of '''<big>I</big>'''nterest\". The planet was found by Wolf Cukier, a [[high school student]], who joined the [[Goddard Space Flight Center]] as a summer intern. He looked through [[Light curve|light curves]] that were flagged as [[eclipsing binaries]] by volunteers of the [[Planet Hunters]] citizen science project.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://exoplanets.nasa.gov/news/1619/discovery-alert-high-school-student-finds-a-world-with-two-suns/|title=Discovery Alert! High School Student Finds a World With Two Suns|website=Exoplanet Exploration: Planets Beyond our Solar System|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref>\n==Planetary system==\n{{OrbitboxPlanet begin\n| table_ref =<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nasa.gov/feature/goddard/2020/nasa-s-tess-mission-uncovers-its-1st-world-with-two-stars|title=TESS Discovers Its 1st Planet Orbiting 2 Stars|first=Francis|last=Reddy|date=January 6, 2020|website=NASA}}</ref> \n}}\n{{OrbitboxPlanet\n| exoplanet = [[TOI-1338 b|b]]\n| mass_earth = \u2265 6.9\n| period = 94\n| semimajor = \n| eccentricity =  \n}}\n{{Orbitbox end}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[TOI 700]]\n\n== References==\n{{reflist}}\n== External link ==\n* [https://www.nasa.gov/tess-transiting-exoplanet-survey-satellite TESS \u2013 Official WebSite]\n* [https://www.discovermagazine.com/the-sciences/nasa-telescope-discovers-its-first-planet-orbiting-two-stars NASA Telescope Discovers Its First Planet Orbiting Two Stars]\n*[https://exofop.ipac.caltech.edu/tess/target.php?id=260128333 TOI 1338 at ExoFOP TESS]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Exoplanet}}\n{{2020 in space}}\n\n[[Category:Planetary systems with one confirmed planet]]\n[[Category:TESS Objects of Interest|1338, TOI]]\n[[Category:Circumbinary planets]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Binary star system}}\n{{use dmy dates |date=January 2020}}\n{{starbox begin\n|name = TOI 1338\n}}\n{{starbox image\n|image = [[File:TOI1338-starmap.png|320px]]\n|caption = Position of TOI 1338 in Pictor\n|credit = \n}}\n{{Starbox observe\n| epoch = J2000\n| constell = [[Pictor]]\n| ra =  {{RA|06|08|31.94}}.<ref name=\"ExoFOP TESS\"/>\n| dec = {{DEC|-59|32|27.55}}.<ref name=\"ExoFOP TESS\"/>\n| appmag_v = 11.975\u00b10.025\n}}\n{{Starbox character\n| type = \n| class = \n| appmag_1_passband = \n| appmag_1 = \n| appmag_2_passband = \n| appmag_2 = \n| appmag_3_passband =\n| appmag_3 =\n| appma