und each other every 14.6 days.<ref name=\"Martin et al\">{{Cite journal|last=Martin|first=David V.|last2=Triaud|first2=Amaury H. M. J.|last3=Udry|first3=Stephane|last4=Marmier|first4=Maxime|last5=Maxted|first5=Pierre F. L.|last6=Cameron|first6=Andrew Collier|last7=Hellier|first7=Coel|last8=Pepe|first8=Francesco|last9=Pollacco|first9=Don|last10=Segransan|first10=Damien|last11=West|first11=Richard|date=April 2019|title=The BEBOP radial-velocity survey for circumbinary planets I. Eight years of CORALIE observations of 47 single-line eclipsing binaries and abundance constraints on the masses of circumbinary planets|url=http://arxiv.org/abs/1901.01627|journal=Astronomy & Astrophysics|volume=624|pages=A68|doi=10.1051/0004-6361/201833669|issn=0004-6361|via=|doi-access=free}}</ref> \n==Nomenclature and history==\nThe acronym '''<big>\"TOI\"</big>''' refers to stars and exoplanets studied by TESS, and is short for: \"'''<big>T</big>'''ransiting Exoplanet Survey Satellite '''<big>O</big>'''bject of '''<big>I</big>'''nterest\". The planet was found by a [[high school student]], who joined the [[Goddard Space Flight Center]] as a summer intern. He looked through [[Light curve|light curves]] that were flagged as [[eclipsing binaries]] by volunteers of the [[Planet Hunters]] citizen science project.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://exoplanets.nasa.gov/news/1619/discovery-alert-high-school-student-finds-a-world-with-two-suns/|title=Discovery Alert! High School Student Finds a World With Two Suns|website=Exoplanet Exploration: Planets Beyond our Solar System|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref>\n==Planetary system==\n{{OrbitboxPlanet begin\n| table_ref =<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nasa.gov/feature/goddard/2020/nasa-s-tess-mission-uncovers-its-1st-world-with-two-stars|title=TESS Discovers Its 1st Planet Orbiting 2 Stars|first=Francis|last=Reddy|date=January 6, 2020|website=NASA}}</ref> \n}}\n{{OrbitboxPlanet\n| exoplanet = [[TOI-1338 b|b]]\n| mass_earth = \u2265 6.9\n| period = 94\n| semima